        <h1 class="chap-title">
            Relations
        </h1>
            <div style="text-align:center">
                <figure class="lead-figure">
                    <img src="graphics/powerset_of_3.svg.png">
                    <figcaption>
                    Powerset of three.
                    </figcaption>
                </figure>
            </div>
            <details>
                <summary class="sum1">
                 Introduction
                </summary>
                <p>
                 In Mathematics, A relation between elements of two sets can
                 occur in many contexts. Like consider a relation between two
                 sets of stations linked through trains.
                </p>
                <p>
                 A relation set between two relations say <i>A</i> and <i>B</i>
                 is a subset of cartesian products of <i>A</i> and <i>B</i>
                </p>
            </details>
            <details>
                <summary class="sum1">
                   Relations and Their Properties
                </summary>
                <details>
                   <summary class="sum2">
                      Introduction
                   </summary>
                   <p>
                     Ordered Pairs can be used to express relation between two elements.
                     These are called as binary relations.
                   </p>

                   <details>
                      <summary class="sum3">
                       DEFINITION 1:
                      </summary>
                      <p>
                        A binary relation from <i>A</i> to <i>B</i> is a subset of <i>A</i> x <i>B</i>;
                      </p>
                      <p>
                       <b>Example</b>
                        Let <i>A</i> &equals; {0,1,2} and <i>B</i> &equals; {1,2}
                        then a relation set of {x | x &isin; R x &equals;x} is given by
                        {1,1} ,{2,2}
                      </p>
                   </details>
               </details>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum2">
                     Functions as Relations
                     </summary>
                     <p>
                      A relation between a function from <i>A</i> to <i>B</i>  is defined by assigning exactly one element of <i>B</i> to <i>A</i>;
                     </p>
                     <p>
                     The graph of <i>f</i> is the set of ordered pairs (<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) such that <i>b</i> &equals; f <i>(a)</i>.
                     </p>
                      <p>
                       <b>Example</b>
                        A relation on a set <i>A</i> is a subset of <i>A</i> x <i>A</i>.
                        Because <i>A</i> x <i>A</i> has n<sup>2</sup> elements
                     </p>
                     <p>
                        when <i>A</i> has <i>n</i> elements, and there are
                        2 n<sup>2</sup> subsets of <i>A</i> x <i>A</i>.
                        Thus, there are 2 n<sup>2</sup> relations on a set with <i>n</i> elements.
                      </p>
                </details>

                <details>
                    <summary class="sum2">
                     Relations on a Set
                    </summary>

                    <details>
                      <summary class="sum3">
                       DEFINITION 2:
                      </summary>
                      <p>
                        A relation on a set <i>A</i> is a relation from <i>A</i> to <i>A</i>.
                      </p>
                    </details>
                  </details>

                  <details>
                      <summary class="sum2">
                       Properties of Relations
                      </summary>

                      <details>
                        <summary class="sum3">
                         DEFINITION 3:
                        </summary>
                        <p>
                          A relation <i>R</i> on a set <i>A</i> is called reflexive if
                          ((<i>a</i>, <i>a</i>) &isin; <i>R</i>) for every element a &isin; <i>A</i>.
                        </p>
                      </details>
                      <details>
                        <summary class="sum3">
                         DEFINITION 4:
                        </summary>
                        <p>
                          A relation <i>R</i> on a set <i>A</i> is called symmetric
                           if (<i>b</i>, <i>a</i>) &isin; <i>R</i> whenever
                           (<i>a</i>,  <i>b</i>) &isin; <i>R</i> , for all
                         </p>
                         <p>
                           <i>a</i>, <i>b</i> &isin; <i>A</i>. A relation <i>R</i> on a set
                           <i>A</i> such that for all <i>a</i>, <i>b</i> &isin; <i>A</i>,
                           if (<i>a</i>,  <i>b</i>) &isin; <i>R</i> and (<i>b</i>, <i>a</i>)
                          &isin; <i>R</i>, then <i>a</i> &equals; <i>b</i> is called antisymmetric.
                        </p>
                      </details>

                      <details>
                         <summary class="sum3">
                        DEFINITION 5:
                         </summary>

                      <p>
                        A relation <i>R</i> on a set <i>A</i> is called transitive if whenever (<i>a</i>,  <i>b</i>) &isin; <i>R</i> and (<i>b</i>, <i>c</i>) &isin; <i>R</i>,
                        then (<i>a</i>, <i>c</i>) &isin; <i>R</i>, for all <i>a </i>, <i>b </i>, <i>c </i> &isin; <i>A</i>.
                      </p>
                      </details>

                      <details>
                        <summary class="sum3">
                       DEFINITION 6:
                        </summary>
                        <p>
                          Let <i>R</i> be a relation from a set <i>A</i>
                          to a set <i>B</i> and <i>S</i> a relation from <i>B</i>
                          to a set <i>C</i>. The composite of <i>R</i> and <i>S</i>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                          is the relation consisting of ordered pairs (<i>a</i>, <i>c</i>),
                          where <i>a</i> &isin; <i>A</i>, <i>c</i> &isin; <i>C</i>,
                           and for which there exists an element <i>b</i> &isin; <i>B</i>
                      </p>
                       <p>
                           such that (<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) &isin; <i>R</i> and (<i>b</i>, <i>c</i>)
                            &isin; <i>S</i>. We denote the composite of <i>R</i> and <i>S</i>
                           by <i>S</i> â—¦<i>R</i>.
                        </p>
                      </details>
                    </details>
                </details>

